## Step {{nextStep}} — Start your first branch

Use the git discipline commands to start work:

{{#cursorEnabled}}
In Cursor, type `/git-start-work feat <scope> <description>` to create
a properly named branch before writing any code.
{{/cursorEnabled}}
{{#claudeEnabled}}
In Claude Code, run `/git-start-work feat <scope> <description>` to create
a properly named branch before writing any code.
{{/claudeEnabled}}

The git commands enforce:
- Branches from up-to-date master/main
- Conventional commit format
- Pre-commit checks (typecheck, lint, test) before every commit
- PR-based workflow — never commit directly to the default branch

## Step {{finalStep}} — Install dependencies and verify the setup

```bash
{{packageManager}} install
{{packageManagerRun}} build
{{packageManagerRun}} typecheck
```

All three should pass on a fresh scaffold. If they don't, something
is misconfigured — fix it before writing any feature code.

## Day-to-day workflow

```
1. /git-start-work     — always start with a branch
2. Write code          — agents read AGENTS.md and canonical docs
3. /git-commit-progress — commit with checks as you go
4. /git-finish-work    — push and open PR when done
5. Review and merge    — human reviews, squash-merges, deletes branch
```

